data.title: September 2017
data.synopsis:
For most people, September signifies the end of summer, which also
means the end of their commitment in the gym for many months. When the
average person isn't so worried about their beach body, they tend to
stop spending time working out and watching what they eat. But you're
not average, are you? Certainly not! Another above average person is
this issue's cover guy: Danny Hester. He is a story of success
through hard work and commitment in every aspect of life. This issue
also features our Hard Body star Lindsay Christiansen who's a mom,
trainer, yogi, fitness star and all-around inspiration for anyone who
wants more out of life. We know this issue will help you on your way
to getting everything you want out of life in and out of the gym.
Here's where you can get started!

data.title: June 2017
data.synopsis: Mark Robinson is leading the health and fitness charge Down Under. The Australian trainer, model, and nutrition expert, better known as “Health Man Mark,” is living proof that world-class aesthetics and a devotion to overall health is not only possible, it’s the perfect synergistic combination. Also in this issue is a key strategy to coax more growth out of your biceps and triceps, but with less muscle damage. Our expert trainer goes through the simple steps you need to take to start getting lean, without a crazy crash diet. We explore the best amino acid supplements that can make a big difference in how you look, feel, and perform. And we introduce the Natural Fit Sisters: full-blooded siblings, bikini pros, and fitness inspirations to anyone who wants to make positive changes in their life. Iron Man Magazine columnists share their thoughts on training intensity, strategic use of range of motion, sneaking some cardio into your lifting routine, and three ingenious new ways to use the cable crossover machine.

data.title: May 2017
data.synopsis: Surgeon, businesswoman, social media influencer, model, and mother, Dr. Cat Begovic embodies the “have it all” ethos that the fitness industry celebrates. Dr. Cat discusses the challenges she faces as a woman in the male-dominated world of plastic surgery, her new line of anti-aging beauty products called M.D. Glam, and one of the most ambitious and sophisticated photo shoots Iron Man Magazine has ever produced. Also in this issue, take your pick from five different time-saving shoulder-scorching workouts, guaranteed to get your delts to finally pop. The return of an IFBB legend inspires an incredible chest-and-tri’s workout, and our nutrition expert examines the ins and outs of a new category of Smart Gainers, advanced formulas designed to help you add more muscle. Check out this must-try experimental night-time strategy that can help you accelerate hypertrophy without accruing muscle damage. The May issue of Iron Man hits newsstands May 1.

data.title: February 2017
data.synopsis: The first annual Iron Man Bikini Pro Issue features the reigning Olympia Bikini Champion Courtney King. Shot on the classic beaches of Southern California, King has never looked fitter or sexier. Half a world away, New Zealand’s Sheena Jayne Martin shows off the kind of body that King is going to have to compete against at the 2017 Mr. Olympia. Like King, Martin’s own story of becoming a pro athlete is filled with moments of drama, doubt, and ultimately, victory. Also in the issue, natural Men’s Physique competitor Dan Zigler demonstrates five unorthodox exercises that all gym-goers should try; Iron Man’s supplement expert explores the latest innovations in protein powder; and we present a rep-intensive introduction to the anabolic technique of EDT. The new issue of Iron Man also includes stories on the best muscle-building herbal supplements, a hit-it-and-quit-it chest workout, an expert advice Q&A on training over 40, and the right way to hit your lats. data.title: January 2017
data.synopsis: Officer Mike Counihan is the fittest cop in New York—and possibly the world. As an active member of the NYPD’s anti-terrorism task force, Counihan’s extreme strength and fitness has literally saved lives, including his own. Men’s Physique superstar Stanislas “Stanimal” De Longeaux goes through a multi-angle chest workout, while CEO Markus Kaulius introduces the reader to his own brutal ab training, which is as creative as it is challenging. IFBB Bikini pro Lorie Forman proves that 40 is the new 20, and shows that age is truly just a number, especially when you’re smoking hot with world-class glutes. Just in time for New Year’s resolutions, a leading sport supplement PhD explores ingredients that can curb hunger. The new issue of Iron Man also includes stories on the anabolic power of sunlight, your ticket to an ultra-fast biceps pump, an expert advice Q&A session, and much more. The January issue of Iron Man hits newsstands January 1.

data.synopsis:
Our August issue, as usual, is an Arnold extravaganza. We always pay homage to the big guy around his birthday, and this year we present his best IRON MAN covers. Amazing stuff—from mountainous biceps to Terminator bad-ass you’ll see it all. Then, Gabriel Wilson, Ph.D., and Jacob Wilson, Ph.D., look at the intriguing research on breakfast and lay out what you should be eating to boost your muscle-building and ripping results. Plus, Dr. Joe Klemczewski tells you how to peak your physique to look your ripped best—whether you’re headed onstage or on vacation. 

Cory Crow gets Matt Christianer’s unique physique-champ perspective on building boulder shoulders. Check out his unique exercises, like barbell lateral raises (yes, with a barbell!), exclusively in the digital version.

data.title: June 2012
data.synopsis:
Los Angeles Fitness Expo BodySpace Spokesmodel Winners Laura Bailey and Craig Capurso in June 2012 Iron Man Magazine

The June IRON MAN is all about winning. No, Charlie Sheen did not make our cover, but the two BodySpace Model Search champions did. You’ll see how Laura Bailey and Craig Capurso put it all together to win it big on the L.A. Fitness Expo stage -- and how you can do it too. 

Dr. Joe Klemczewski continues his tips on getting freaky ripped, pro Dan Hill reveals his quad-building program, and Bill Dobbins, co-author of Arnold’s Encyclopedia of Modern Bodybuilding, has tricks for how to pack your midback with mass. Speaking of Arnold, check out the big in-your-face photos from the Arnold Classic.


REACH YOUR GOALS
Each month plug yourself back in and recharge lagging motivation by subscribing to Iron Man magazine. How does one reach their goals? By staying motivated, sticking to the workout program and getting to the next level.

APRIL ISSUE 75TH ANNIVERSARY EDITION

data.title: March 2012
data.synopsis: Our March issue gets a mass-with-class blast from the past. L.T. does the Q&A thing with none other than legendary Lee Labrada. You won't believe Lee's mind-blowing size and condition at age 51. He'll reveal all his secrets, from his growth-threshold workout to his dial-it-in diet. Next, we hit the squat rack with pro Derik Farnsworth. True, he’s 5'2", but he recently squatted 405—for 30 reps (yes, in a row)! We’ll give you the full story and his magic leg-training methods. Also, Mr. America Doug Brignole expounds on his new findings regarding a better way to pack on muscle—exciting stuff!
